ANTHRAX, HUMAN & LIVESTOCK - ROMANIA (DANUBE DELTA)
***************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
See Also
Anthrax, human - Romania 2000.0737
Anthrax, cattle - Romania 19990625112603
Date: Wed, 19 Jul 2000 09:58:40 -0500
From: H. Larry Penning <bevpenn@fgi.net> & M. Cosgriff
<mcosgriff@hotmail.com> & Dr. James B. Kiracofe <drkiracofe@mindspring.com>
& John S. Marr, MD <jsmarr@javanet.com>
Source: Reuters & Associated Press
<http://newsnet.reuters.com/cgi-bin/basketview.cgi?b=rcom:health&s=nL1983971>
<http://www.nandotimes.com>

One man died after being infected with anthrax [_Bacillus anthracis_ and 6
members of his family are believed to have contracted the disease after it
killed dozens of livestock in a Danube Delta village, a health official
said Wednesday.
"So far there is one confirmed death from anthrax, a farmer who ate
contaminated pork," said Marian Avram, chief sanitary - veterinary
inspector of the Tulcea county. Avram said nine people suspected of anthrax
infection had been rushed to hospital in Tulcea, the main Danube Delta port
town, 260 km (160 miles) east of Bucharest.
He said the epidemic was declared 2 weeks ago when the Danube Delta, like
the rest of Romania, was hit by the worst drought in a century.
Local authorities have declared a quarantine in Mahmudia and Murighiol, 2
small downstream ports with a total population of 16 000, and closed access
to the Delta in those areas.
"Containment of the disease would be difficult, as the villagers of
Mahmudia keep some 900 horses and 450 cattle in a half- domesticated
condition on [the Danube reefs, and do not report them to authorities to
avoid taxation," said veterinarian Marian Avram, of Tulcea county health
authorities. Already 70 head of cattle, horses and pigs have died of
anthrax, Avram said.
Veterinary inspectors found that the man who died had slaughtered a pig and
[eaten the meat together with his family, in spite of the ban ordered by
authorities on the consumption of animal products at Mahmudia, about 150
miles northeast of Bucharest. Another man is suspected to have contracted
the disease because he handled the skin of a horse he found dead on the
reefs in the
Danube River delta, Avram said.
In a previous case of anthrax 3 months ago, a hospital in the eastern city
of Buzau treated 6 people who ate an infected lamb. No one died.
Last year, an outbreak of anthrax killed four cattle in northeast Romania.
